# Pipeline self-modification guard (F1-S7, issue #10; AGENTS.md "Pipeline
# self-modification"; factory.md §13 point 3).
#
# Mirrors PROTECTED_PATH_PREFIXES / PROTECTED_EXACT_PATHS in
# scripts/factory/implement-patch-logic.mts's findForbiddenPatchPaths
# exactly — that function already rejects any implementing agent's patch
# that touches these paths at all (a fail-closed publish-time guard, unit
# tested); this file adds the complementary human-review control at the
# GitHub level (required code-owner review, once branch protection's
# require_code_owner_reviews is enabled) for the conventional, human
# -directed PRs that legitimately DO touch these paths. Keep the two lists
# in lockstep: any path added to one belongs in the other.
#
# The invariant both controls enforce together: an implementing agent can
# never grant itself more pipeline power, and a human changing pipeline
# power always goes through an explicit, visible review by the operator.

# The factory's own workflow files — triggers, permissions, secrets,
# action pins, allowlists.
/.github/ @syamaner

# The privileged glue/publisher scripts (read-only-agent /
# privileged-publisher split, factory.md §13) — these decide what an
# agent's patch is allowed to do, so they must never be self-editable by
# that same patch.
/scripts/factory/ @syamaner

# The spec-grounded-review skill: claude-code-review.yml's restore step
# re-applies this path unconditionally from PR-head, the same treatment
# as scripts/factory/ (see findForbiddenPatchPaths's own docstring for
# the full reasoning) — so it needs the same human-review control.
/.claude/skills/spec-grounded-review/ @syamaner

# This file itself — an agent (or anyone) editing CODEOWNERS to drop a
# protected path must go through the same review the paths it protects
# require, not bypass it by editing the control.
/CODEOWNERS @syamaner
